{{Infobox pipeline | name = Bukhara–Tashkent–Bishkek–Almaty pipeline | type = natural gas | map = Казахстан и СредАзия газопроводы.png | map_caption = Location of Bukhara–Tashkent–Bishkek–Almaty pipeline | country = [[Uzbekistan]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], [[Kazakhstan]] | coordinates = | photo = | caption = | operator = [[Uzbekneftegas]], KyrKazGas, KazTransGas | partners = [[Uzbekneftegas]], Kyrgyzgas, [[KazMunayGas]] | length_km = | discharge = 22&nbsp;billion cubic meters | direction = west–east | start = [[Bukhara]], [[Uzbekistan]] | finish = [[Almaty]], [[Kazakhstan]] | est = 1971 | through = [[Tashkent]], [[Shymkent]], [[Taraz]], [[Bishkek]] | par = }}
The '''Bukhara–Tashkent–Bishkek–Almaty pipeline''' is a [[Uzbekistan]]'s main natural gas export pipeline.
==History== Construction of the pipeline started in 1967. In 1968, the pipeline reached to Tashkent, in 1970 to Bishkek (then Frunze) and in 1971 to Almaty.<ref name=geopolitics> {{cite book | last = Brill Olcott | first = Martha | editor1-last = Victor | editor1-first = David G. | editor2-last = Jaffe | editor2-first = Amy | editor3-last = Hayes | editor3-first = Mark H. | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4eYAUWFZz8gC&pg=RA3-PA222 | title= Natural gas and geopolitics: from 1970 to 2040 | chapter = The Transport of Turkmen Gas: Existing Alternatives | publisher= [[Cambridge University Press]] | year=2006 | page =222 | isbn = 978-0-521-86503-6 | accessdate=2009-07-19}} </ref>
==Description== The diameter of the pipeline is {{convert|1020|mm|in|0}} and the annual capacity of the pipeline is almost 22 billion cubic meter (bcm) of natural gas.<ref name=uzbekistan> {{Cite journal | last = Sagdullaev | first = Djakhangir | url = http://deposit.ddb.de/cgi-bin/dokserv?idn=976406306&dok_var=d1&dok_ext=pdf&filename=976406306.pdf | title = Energy Policy, Economic Cooperation, and Sustainable Development in Central Asia: the case of Uzbekistan | publisher = [[University of Giessen|Justus-Liebig-Universität]] | format = PDF | year = 2005 | accessdate = 2008-02-16 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110522080757/http://deposit.ddb.de/cgi-bin/dokserv?idn=976406306&dok_var=d1&dok_ext=pdf&filename=976406306.pdf | archivedate = 2011-05-22 | df = }} </ref> The Bukhara–Tashkent–Bishkek–Almaty pipeline is the main source of gas supply for [[Kyrgyzstan]] and southern part of [[Kazakhstan]]. It is possible that the pipeline will be connected with the planned [[Central Asia-China gas pipeline]].<ref name=dundee> {{cite journal |journal=The CEPMLP Internet Journal |first=Mehmet |last=Ögütçü |url=http://www.dundee.ac.uk/cepmlp/journal/html/Vol17/Vol17_8.pdf |title=Kazakhstan's expanding cross-border gas links. Implications for Europe, Russia, China and other CIS countries. Presented at the Windsor Energy Group’s Regional Pipelines Roundtable, Almaty |publisher=The Centre for Energy, Petroleum and Mineral Law and Policy at the [[University of Dundee]] |volume=17 |issue=8 |format=PDF |date=2006-10-02 |accessdate=2008-02-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929134259/http://www.dundee.ac.uk/cepmlp/journal/html/Vol17/Vol17_8.pdf |archivedate=2007-09-29 |df= }} </ref>
==Operators== The Kazakhstan section of pipeline is operated by KazTransGas, a wholly owned subsidiary of [[KazMunayGas]]. The Kyrgyzstan section of pipe line is operated by KyrKazGas, the joint venture of KazTransGas and Kyrgyzgas.
==Future developments== The technical condition of the pipeline is alarming, particularly in Kyrgyzstan. Therefore, there are plans for construction of a second trunk gas pipeline and renovation of the existing pipeline.<ref name=tacis> {{Cite journal | url=http://delkaz.ec.europa.eu/joomla/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=56&Itemid=66 | title=Energy | publisher=The European Commission's Delegation to Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan | date=2006-12-04 | accessdate=2008-02-16 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} </ref>
