{{Refimprove|date=February 2017}}
The term '''die shrink''' (sometimes '''optical shrink''' or '''process shrink''') refers to a simple semiconductor scaling of [[semiconductor device]]s, mainly [[transistor]]s. The act of shrinking a [[Die (integrated circuit)|die]] is to create a somewhat identical circuit using a more advanced [[Semiconductor device fabrication|fabrication]] process, usually involving an advance of [[lithography|lithographic]] [[semiconductor node|node]]. This reduces overall costs for a chip company, as the absence of major architectural changes to the processor lowers research and development costs, while at the same time allowing more processor dies to be manufactured on the same piece of [[silicon wafer]], resulting in less cost per product sold.
==Details== Die shrinks are the key to improving price/performance at semiconductor companies such as [[Intel]], [[Advanced Micro Devices|AMD]] (including the former [[ATI Technologies|ATI]]), [[Nvidia|NVIDIA]], and [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung]]. Examples in the 2000s include the codenamed [[Pentium 4#Cedar Mill|Cedar Mill]] [[Pentium 4]] processors (from [[90&nbsp;nm]] [[CMOS]] to [[65&nbsp;nm]] [[CMOS]]) and [[Penryn (microarchitecture)|Penryn Core 2]] processors (from [[65&nbsp;nm]] CMOS to [[45&nbsp;nm]] CMOS), the codenamed [[Athlon 64 X2#Brisbane (65 nm SOI)|Brisbane]] [[Athlon 64 X2]] processors (from [[90&nbsp;nm]] [[Silicon on insulator|SOI]] to [[65&nbsp;nm]] [[Silicon on insulator|SOI]]), and various generations of [[Graphics processing unit|GPU]]s from both ATI and NVIDIA. In January 2010, Intel released [[Clarkdale (microprocessor)|Clarkdale]] [[List of Intel Core i5 microprocessors|Core i5]] and [[Intel Core#Core i7|Core i7]] processors fabricated with a [[32&nbsp;nm]] process, down from a previous [[45&nbsp;nm]] process used in older iterations of the [[Nehalem (microarchitecture)|Nehalem]] [[Central processing unit|processor]] [[microarchitecture]]. Intel, in particular, formerly focused on leveraging die shrinks to improve product performance at a regular cadence through its [[Tick-Tock model]]. In this [[business model]], every new [[microarchitecture]] (tick) is followed by a die shrink (tock) to improve performance with the same microarchitecture.<ref name="anandtech-pao">{{cite web|title=Intel’s ‘Tick-Tock’ Seemingly Dead, Becomes ‘Process-Architecture-Optimization’|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/10183/intels-tick-tock-seemingly-dead-becomes-process-architecture-optimization|website=Anandtech|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref>
Die shrinks are beneficial to end-users as shrinking a die reduces the current used by each transistor switching on or off in semiconductor devices while maintaining the same clock frequency of a chip, making a product with less power consumption (and thus less heat production), increased [[clock rate]] headroom, and lower prices.<ref name="anandtech-pao" /> Since the cost to fabricate a 200-mm or 300-mm silicon wafer is proportional to the number of fabrication steps, and not proportional to the number of chips on the wafer, die shrinks cram more chips onto each wafer, resulting in lowered manufacturing costs per chip.
==Half-shrink== {{Semiconductor manufacturing processes}}
In CPU fabrications, a die shrink always involves an advance to a [[lithography|lithographic]] node as defined by [[International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors|ITRS]] (see list at right). For GPU and [[System on a chip|SoC]] manufacturing, the die shrink often involves shrinking the die on a node not defined by the ITRS, for instance the 150&nbsp;nm, 110&nbsp;nm, 80&nbsp;nm, 55&nbsp;nm, 40&nbsp;nm and more currently 14&nbsp;nm nodes, sometimes referred to as "half-nodes". This is a stopgap between two ITRS-defined [[lithography|lithographic]] nodes (thus called a "half-node shrink") before further shrink to the lower ITRS-defined nodes occurs, which helps save further R&D cost. The choice to perform die shrinks to either full-nodes or half-nodes rests with the foundry and not the integrated circuit designer.
